# Code Quality

## Naming

- Names reveal intent: `calculateOrderTotal`, not `process` or `handleData`.
- Booleans read as questions: `isActive`, `hasPermission`, `canCheckout`.
- Avoid abbreviations unless universally known (`id`, `url`, `api`).

## Functions & Files

- Target ≤ 30 lines per function; split when longer.
- ≤ 5 parameters; use an object/options type when more are needed.
- One primary export per file when possible; colocate related helpers.

## Errors & Validation

- Fail fast at system boundaries (HTTP input, env, file I/O, external APIs).
- Never swallow errors silently. Log context, then rethrow or return a typed error.
- Validate untrusted input at the edge; trust internal code after validation.

## Comments & Docs

- Code should mostly explain itself. Comment *why*, not *what*.
- No commented-out code. No TODO without a ticket or immediate follow-up.

## Security & Config

- No secrets, tokens, or credentials in source. Use env vars.
- No hardcoded URLs, ports, or paths that differ per environment.

## Tests

- Test behavior, not implementation details.
- Cover happy path, one edge case, and one failure path for new logic.
- Do not add tests that only assert the obvious (getters, trivial wrappers).

## Before Shipping

- Run lint/typecheck for the touched stack.
- Review your own diff: unrelated changes, debug logs, and scope creep.
